        <div id="dsq-comment-body-69162" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-69162" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I was impressed with Mark Potts and his effort. To the commenter above looking for a &#8220;meatier dissection&#8221; I&#8217;ll offer this uninformed opinion: </p>
<p>If Backfence was still publishing, today&#8217;s topic would have been whether it could compete against the Washington Post&#8217;s just launched hyperlocal effort, LoudonExtra.com</p>
<p>What the Washington Post is doing in Loudon County is very similar to what Backfence pioneered. The Post is planning to launch its own version of hyperlocal throughout the Metro area. </p>
<p>The Backfence model is very much alive. </p>
<p>I think Mark does a pretty good job in spelling out what happened. Sure, his points may appear as conventional wisdom to the wags but the big difference is Backfence actually executed on it. </p>
<p>Even if Mark provided every ounce of detail about what was right and wrong with meeting its vision, it still wouldn&#8217;t tell you whether the vision is flawed. And that&#8217;s really what it&#8217;s about, isn&#8217;t it? </p>
<p>I know nothing about what may have gone right or wrong with Backfence, but I know from my own experiences in this that it&#8217;s rarely the vision that will cause the most grief, but the hundreds of other things you have bring in place to make it happen. </p>
<p>But to the point about the Post: The Post&#8217;s hyperlocal efforts can be mundane to the point of sleepy and still drive mountains of traffic to its site. Backfence didn&#8217;t have that luxury, and as Mark pointed out one of the issues that hyperlocal content has is, well, it&#8217;s hyperlocal. </p>
<p>So really, the question again is how do you create a hyperlocal site that can compete against a major media outlet? Not such a new question here, is it?  </p>
