            <div id="dsq-comment-message-69382" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Ms. Useem is right.  But maybe Mark is too close to what happened, and too sure the model he helped developed is absolutely right, to give a useful postmortem.  A clue to what went wrong with Backfence, I think, is Mark&#8217;s persistent claim that local-local content anywhere is and ought to be &#8220;mundane.&#8221;  A browsing of Mike    Orren&#8217;s pegasusnews.com, which covers the communities of Dallas/Fort Worth, shows that local-local can be out of the ordinary, fresh and imaginative &#8212; all antonyms for &#8220;mundane.&#8221;  Some of the subjects Pegasus News covers may indeed be ordinary, but Mike and his staff bring energy, and a sassy-edged humor, to their site.  They are not sitting back with their feet on the desk, waiting for contributors to decide what shall be written about, and how.  They roll up their sleeves and get engaged.  They proclaim their passionate feelings for Dallas/Fort Worth.  They have a love-hate relationship &#8212; mostly, to be sure, love &#8212; with their communities, and  that courses through the site.  It&#8217;s one reasons, I&#8217;m sure, that Fisher Communications swooped down and bought Pegasus News at about the same time that Backfence was going out of business.  </p>
